The legal team is led by Busiro East MP Medard Sseggona of Lukwago & Company Advocates.
Mr Harriet Ssali Nalukwago, the Supreme Court registrar, said hearing of the petition will begin 10 days after the respondents are served.
Electoral laws
In the petition, Bobi Wine avers that “The presidential election held on the 14th day of January 2021 was not held in accordance with the provisions of the electoral laws and the principles governing elections, which non-compliance affected the results of the election in a substantial manner”.
He adds: “The 1st respondent (Mr Museveni) was not validly elected as the president. His election be annulled and set aside and a fresh election be conducted in accordance with the law.”
On January 28, the Electoral Commission Chairperson Justice Simon Byabakama released the final presidential results indicating that Mr Museveni won with six million votes (58.38 per cent) against Wine’s 3.6 million votes (35 per cent).
Wine rejected the results as manufactured, claiming, without evidence, that he won.
Under this ground, Bobi Wine contends that the presidential elections were not conducted in accordance with principles laid down in the Constitution, the Presidential Elections Act and the Electoral Commission Act.



